Notebook[{
Cell["Tropical Convexity Tutorial", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"136ccd12-2452-49ba-874d-f56f00023708"],

Cell["\<\
A walkthrough of the graph translation of tropical convexity: tropical \
segments as geodesics, geodesic convex hulls, and median structure. Worked \
examples on paths, cycles, grids, and median graphs. The min-plus arithmetic \
side (TropicalPlus / TropicalDot / TropicalMatrixPower) now lives in \
Code/TropicalOperations.wl in the dev repo and is no longer part of the \
paclet.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"05d346c8-d969-4ba4-a903-bf2eb69d5c59"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a49849b3-9a87-45e2-89ac-a6a912a397b7"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"b2cb2538-84ee-4816-8a64-0354fc523225"],

Cell["Tropical segments as geodesics", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a455deab-f2c2-41b4-a316-f6d0b98e7344"],

Cell["\<\
Under the shortest-path metric, a tropical segment from u to v is the vertex \
set of any geodesic between them. The graph-side enumerator is FindSegment; \
multi-valued when the geodesic is non-unique.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d4d33f34-b838-4905-b785-3a6fa90bf786"],

Cell["FindSegment[PathGraph[Range[5]], 1, 5, All]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"9fcaa01c-8c5e-4d9d-bb6a-6c864f0017b3"],

Cell["\<\
On a 6-cycle antipodal vertices admit two distinct geodesics (one for each \
side of the cycle):\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"2fc171f5-9b5e-4c57-8459-804c7f820567"],

Cell["FindSegment[CycleGraph[6], 1, 4, All]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"496cc068-1e8a-4734-aa32-d920fd04ae0c"],

Cell["Geodesic convexity", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"48f43d44-3ab7-47d3-9066-c5d702f4953a"],

Cell["\<\
A vertex set S is geodesically convex if every geodesic between vertices in S \
stays inside S.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"46c49145-899c-4974-9bd5-c1739f219cca"],

Cell["\<\
A path is convex (geodesics in a path graph are unique and stay on the path):\
\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"1d7d2539-c3ea-4615-aa4c-8a07f7f9c0af"],

Cell["GeodesicallyConvexQ[PathGraph[Range[7]], {2, 3, 4, 5}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"5b68881d-a3df-4b1e-bb7f-ed376d4b7f6b"],

Cell["\<\
A grid corner pair plus the centre is not convex (geodesics may detour \
through other vertices):\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"48294727-8592-4d8d-aefd-75257da5d34a"],

Cell["GeodesicallyConvexQ[GridGraph[{3, 3}], {1, 5, 9}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"5f9c20a1-44d3-497e-9127-5f7211b00e99"],

Cell["Geodesic convex hull", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d369fd55-97ce-4ecd-9441-c0bc83225743"],

Cell["\<\
FindGeodesicConvexHull returns the smallest geodesically convex superset of a \
vertex set.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"31e18d58-e30d-425c-ac8d-6917244af139"],

Cell["FindGeodesicConvexHull[GridGraph[{3, 3}], {1, 9}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"cbd9eb8f-657a-478e-8f4e-f8efc52dbc4a"],

Cell["\<\
The hull of two opposite corners in a 3x3 grid is the entire grid (every \
vertex sits on some 1-9 geodesic).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0aa0e9bc-ad2a-44da-a01f-e3eefd68d519"],

Cell["FindGeodesicConvexHull[PathGraph[Range[7]], {3, 5}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"7d8e0049-6723-4e17-a202-27c274367a16"],

Cell["\<\
In a path graph the hull of {3, 5} is the closed sub-path {3, 4, 5}.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f6b48ea2-fe97-4725-9160-f3bc46eb0c26"],

Cell["T1 in our reading", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d3b05d93-1832-4bb2-a536-e5b5531e843d"],

Cell["\<\
The first tropical axiom states that every two vertices admit a tropical \
segment. In our reading this is exactly graph connectedness, equivalent to \
ConnectedGraphQ.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a2e75e0a-8252-48b1-b8c7-b7b8e52d6ee0"],

Cell["ConnectedGraphQ[GridGraph[{3, 3}]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"7917590b-d4d1-4b27-a028-81d5824afe13"],

Cell["ConnectedGraphQ[Graph[{1 -> 2, 3 -> 4}]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"820b91b7-c374-4338-a97f-91054d354e35"],

Cell["Uniqueness", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"0005f571-baff-4a53-bd40-91a431165500"],

Cell["\<\
UniqueSegmentQ tests whether the geodesic from u to v is single-valued. On a \
tree it is always true; on a cycle the antipode breaks uniqueness.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"24c583ed-10e4-4182-95d7-8a8c91d6c861"],

Cell["UniqueSegmentQ[PathGraph[Range[7]], 2, 6]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"1a736674-7a84-4d0d-b0ea-d0d91f708e78"],

Cell["UniqueSegmentQ[CycleGraph[6], 1, 4]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"d90b29f7-ae7b-47d8-ba54-b6eae4da5b21"],

Cell["Median graphs and convexity", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"14704d56-b459-4ac7-82f8-5eb4bc250cbf"],

Cell["\<\
A graph is a median graph iff every triple of vertices has a unique median (a \
vertex minimising the sum of distances to the triple). Median graphs have \
especially well-behaved tropical convexity: geodesic convex hulls are closed \
under tropical median.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"31eac9e9-5355-4660-9bf9-2b2de0f8d761"],

Cell["MedianVertices[HypercubeGraph[3], {1, 4, 6}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"89c3e872-c4fa-466c-9eeb-7873ae711300"],

Cell["Hypercubes are median graphs; trees are too.", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d6786ed1-8e72-4ea7-92ec-dc2df165785b"],

Cell["Visualization", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"1e75c2fb-1c95-411a-9ff7-83a72ac74a7a"],

Cell["\<\
Render geodesic hulls and segments through the same diffuse-rendering \
pipeline as the Euclidean layer.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"08a6e5de-da4c-4bce-9a95-57c42df477ea"],

Cell["g = GridGraph[{3, 3}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"b35fa79f-c6c8-47ee-aa2a-f8e1d66e4040"],

Cell["\<\
With[{hull = FindGeodesicConvexHull[g, {1, 9}]}, InfraSceneHighlight[g, \
{InfraPoint[hull] -> Red}]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"489946be-118e-494e-b4d0-b129a73b628a"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"fd5f9406-2357-4d9a-af50-4026ac448a21"],

Cell["TropicalConvexityGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"4c0f4a41-ea57-45e7-a824-2026b13acea2"],

Cell["MetricAlgebraGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d6518e02-0ce9-4904-852c-ea0b48789ad4"],

Cell["EuclideanGeometryTutorial", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"e1cc2aa2-863b-46f7-868f-c9e93cd4e8d9"],

Cell["FindSegment", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"302f0064-03be-4c1c-84e8-e60bd7606dcf"],

Cell["FindGeodesicConvexHull", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b3187a72-98e2-404b-a63e-fc1ef5bf1675"],

Cell["GeodesicallyConvexQ", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"f319e372-97c9-4169-8acd-d30426e6d72b"],

Cell["MedianVertices", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"bde202f7-66a7-4172-894d-f1977b476d08"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"b126420c-a579-42cc-b785-3c5594480b86"],

Cell["\<\
Maclagan and Sturmfels, Introduction to Tropical Geometry, AMS GSM 161, 2015, \
https://janos.cs.technion.ac.il/COURSES/238900-13/Tropical/MaclaganSturmfels.\
pdf\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d42ed17e-7c75-420d-b62d-cd5871f931ef"],

Cell["\<\
Develin and Sturmfels, Tropical Convexity, Documenta Math. 9, 2004, \
https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0308254\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ca640255-dcf6-438c-b4af-9e8c89dd0ca3"],

Cell["\<\
Mulder, The Interval Function of a Graph, Mathematical Centre Tracts 132, \
1980.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7bbaefe2-44a7-49ae-a7ee-b3a64bd3519e"],

Cell["\<\
Bandelt and Mulder, Distance-Hereditary Graphs, J. Combin. Theory Ser. B 41, \
182-208, 1986.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"952b537f-463e-434d-af0a-4280ca19a839"]
},
